  "body": "<!-- **Are you in the right place?**\r\n1. For issues or feature requests, please create an issue in this repository.\r\n2. For general technical and non-technical questions, we are happy to help you on our [Rook.io Slack](https://slack.rook.io/).\r\n3. Did you already search the existing open issues for anything similar? -->\r\n\r\n**Is this a bug report or feature request?**\r\n* Bug Report\r\n\r\n**Deviation from expected behavior:**\r\nThe CrashCollector pod remains in `pending` state indefinitely after running on a k8s node that was pending. There is no way to remove the pod after the node is gone since the kubelet cannot respond on that node.\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior:**\r\nThe CrashCollector pod should be removed automatically by its controller when the other Ceph daemon pods are evicted from the node. As long as the node is drained before being removed, this should give the crash collector pod a chance to be removed.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (minimal and precise):**\r\n<!-- Please let us know any circumstances for reproduction of your bug. -->\r\n- Install Ceph on several nodes\r\n- Remove one of the nodes\r\n- See the crashcollector pod remain in pending state waiting for the node to start again.\r\n\r\nAs a workaround, the deployment should be able to be removed manually before removing the node.\r\n- Drain the node\r\n- Delete the crashcollector deployment\r\n- Remove the node\r\n",
